Description. Male (
holotype
).

Prosoma:
Carapace pale yellow, only faintly marked by cephalic grooves (
Figs 1, 2
), ocular region darker; surface coated with long, pale setae which are darker distally (

Fig. 
1

). Carapace oblongorbiculate, with anterior margin truncate, distally rounded, widest at the level between coxae II and III (
Fig 1, 2
.) Fovea long and straight. Eyes vestigial or poorly developed (
Figs 1, 4
). Clypeus pale orange, with bordered margins that overlie cheliceral boss (

Fig. 
4

). Chilum divided, thin and large. Chelicerae vertical, pale yellow, anterior surface coated with erect long setae (

Fig. 
4

); promargin of chelicerae with three teeth proximally, the median tooth longest (

Fig. 
21

); retromargin with four equally spaced teeth, located at median region of cheliceral furrow (arrow, 

Fig. 
21

). Labium brown, longer than wide (

Fig. 
3

). Endites pale yellow; subrectangular, sides parallel, longer than wide, narrower distally (

Fig. 
3

). Sternum pale yellow, rounded, wider than long, without extensions between coxae, with narrow edge at each coxal joint (

Fig. 
3

); posterior margin not extending between coxae IV but almost fused to extremely narrow, ventral pedicel sclerite (

Fig. 
3

); surface coated with erect setae increasing distally in number.

Opisthosoma: Abdomen pale yellow, oval, longer than wide, without anterior or dorsal scutum (
Fig. 2
). Spinnerets: ALS longest, composed of two articles, basal one expanded anteriomedially; PMS smallest, oval, composed of one article; PLS shorter than ALS, finger-shaped, composed of two articles, basal one extended anteriomedially. Plate of genital gonopore darker, wider than long.

Palp : Segments elongated (
Fig. 2
). Patella slightly widened distally. RTA short, curved in retrolateral view, basally with sclerotized brownish spot (
Fig. 6
). Cymbium covered with dense setae (
Figs 6 –8
,
9, 12
). Subtegulum and tegulum with interlocking lobes (
Fig. 5
). MA large, slightly curved, without denticles (
Figs 5 –7
, 9, 10, 12 ). Embolus distally curved, accompanied by leaf-shaped hyaline conductor ( Figs 9, 11 ).

Prosoma: Chelicerae as male; promargin with three teeth proximally, median tooth longest; retromargin with three teeth, median tooth longest (arrow,
Fig. 22
).

Opisthosoma:
Spinnerets: ALS longest, separated each other, composed of two articles, basal one expanded anteriomedially; 
PMS
smallest, oval, longitudinally extended, composed of one article; PLS shorter than ALS, finger-shaped, composed of two articles (
Figs 13, 14
). Cribellum absent (
Figs 13, 14
), colulus composed only for few and small setae (arrows, 
Figs 13, 14
).

Epigynum: Median septum pear-shaped, strongly sclerotized, lateral lobes are more separated than in the other species (
Fig. 15
). Spermathecae oval, separated, with fertilization ducts near epigastric furrow (
Fig. 18
). [Note: The epigynum of one female ( CNAN T0818, from Río Hondo Cave) was lost before a dorsal view could be photographed, although a ventral view had been obtained (
Fig. 15
); therefore, we show a drawing done previously (
Fig. 18
)].

Variation. Females from Sumidero del Higo are darker and larger than the male and female from Río Hondo Cave. The continuous variation in the epigyna was the criterion for assigning the females to the same species (
Figs 15–17
); the median septum of epigyna have the same pear-shape, but in the females from Sumidero del Higo the posterior part is thinner and the median septum is not so close to the epigastric furrow as in the epigynum of female from Río Hondo ( Figs 16, 17 ). There is variation internally in epigyna; in the largest female the spermathecae has a lateral concavity (
Fig. 20
); in the smallest female from Sumidero del Higo and female from Río Hondo Cave have a similar oval shape ( Figs 18, 19 ). Females: Sumidero del Higo (n= 2 ): Caparace length: 3.90 , 4.95 , width: 2.85 , 3.60 ; tibia I: 3.80 , 5.00/ metatarsus I: 3.38 , 4.50 ; II: 3.80 , 4.95 / 3.50 , 4.60 ; III: 3.40 , 4.60 / 3.00, 5.10 ; IV: 4.10 , 5.40 / 5.50 , 7.30 .

Distribution. Known only from the localities of the type material (
Fig. 28
).
